  "prompt": "Why do so many animals have a tail?",
  "response": "Tails serve various important functions for animals across different species:\n\n1. Balance\n- Helps animals maintain stability while moving\n- Crucial for climbing, running, and navigating complex environments\n- Especially important for animals like cats, monkeys, and squirrels\n\n2. Communication\n- Many animals use tails to signal emotions or intentions\n- Dogs wag their tails to show friendliness or excitement\n- Some animals use tail movements to warn or intimidate others\n\n3. Locomotion\n- Provides additional propulsion for swimming\n- Helps with steering and maneuvering\n- Important for fish, marine mammals, and some reptiles\n\n4. Thermoregulation\n- Some animals use tails to regulate body temperature\n- Can help dissipate heat or conserve warmth\n- Examples include foxes and some desert animals\n\n5. Defense\n- Can be used as a weapon against predators\n- Some animals can detach their tails as a survival mechanism\n- Lizards are a classic example of this adaptation\n\n6. Counterweight\n- Helps maintain body alignment during movement\n- Important for animals that need precise movement\n- Seen in many predators and agile animals\n\nThese diverse functions explain why tails have evolved in so many animal species.",
